<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
This is the only representative of the large, entirely Old World 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Argyreia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Argyreia</taxonomicName>
Clade that occurs in the Neotropics.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
• Species 394-397 form a clade of morphologically very similar species, native to the neotropics. Molecular studies using 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">ITS</emphasis>
strongly suggest that 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="abutiloides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea abutiloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pearceana">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. pearceana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are sisters of the African species 
<taxonomicName authority="Oliv." authorityName="Oliv." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="shirensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea shirensis</emphasis>
Oliv.
</taxonomicName>
, which is very similar morphologically to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sericosepala">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">I. sericosepala</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
